<h1>The Road Back to the College Football Field</h1>
<h3>What Amari Rodgers and Data Sets Can Teach Us About the Challenges Involved</h3>

<p>Have you ever heard of Amari Rodgers? He is a terrific athlete competing at a high level at Clemson University. Rodgers tore his ACL, which is one of the most detrimental injuries an athlete can experience. Not only is it extremely painful when you tear it but the recovery process is long – typically 10 months – and filled with physical pain and mental challenges. Rodgers worked incredibly hard at his rehabilitation and miraculously was jogging on the football field three short months after surgery. Over the next few weeks he was progressively getting faster and eventually sprinting a mere few weeks after just jogging. His father being the assistant coach for another big time program, University of Texas, knows how these recoveries go. So you could only imagine his surprise when Mr. Rogers and the Clemson head coach were texting about Amari’s speedy recovery and progress. A source fromESPN was able to get some of their conversation and as Mr. Rogers inquired from a, “Is he serious—he jogging?” Dabo Swinney, Clemson’s coach, replied. ‘Yeah, he’s progressing really fast!””. He was even making sharp cuts on the practice fields. Rodgers was stunned, proud, and maybe a bit worried things were moving too quickly.</p>

