<p>We know that Amari Rodgers is the exception, not the rule. We also know that athletes put their bodies through tremendous stress and strain when competing at the collegiate level. According to Syracuse University Athletic Trainer, Brandon Hall and Assistant A.D. for Football Performance, Sean Edinger, from interviews I conducted, both said that the most common injury in college football is a sprained ankle, because of all the cutting, hesitations, and stop and go movement athletes have to do on a daily basis for hours on end. That stated, they also agreed that the most detrimental and the hardest injury to regain your full potential from is an ACL tear – what Amari Rodgers had – and what makes his story so remarkable. Finally, they added that the two most injury prone positions are running backs and wide receivers, which makes perfect sense if you understand all the cutting, starting, and stopping they needed to do to be effective in their role.</p>

<p>Once we discussed injuries I then asked them about the toll it takes on the athletes mentally. According to the trainers, this part of the recovery process is overlooked. Coming back from a traumatic injury is clearly very physically demanding, but also mentally – creating doubt and skepticism you can return to form and also the fear that such an injury creates and the possibility it could happen again. Hall and Edinger explained the dynamic further, “Athletes come back from these severe injuries by doing the same motions that they injured themselves with.”</p>

<iframe title="College Football Injuries by Anatomic Site" aria-label="Column Chart" id="datawrapper-chart-dmCjJ" src="https://datawrapper.dwcdn.net/dmCjJ/2/" scrolling="no" frameborder="0" style="width: 0; min-width: 100% !important; border: none;" height="398"></iframe><script type="text/javascript">!function(){"use strict";window.addEventListener("message",(function(e){if(void 0!==e.data["datawrapper-height"]){var t=document.querySelectorAll("iframe");for(var a in e.data["datawrapper-height"])for(var r=0;r<t.length;r++){if(t[r].contentWindow===e.source)t[r].style.height=e.data["datawrapper-height"][a]+"px"}}}))}();
