<p>Taking a step back more broadly, there is ample data to support the amazing recovery of Rodgers and to reinforce what Hall and Edinger are asserting.  They talked about the recovery process in which they take athletes through to get them back on the field. A study of college football player injuries entitled “Injury Rates in a National Sample of College Football Teams: A 2-Year Prospective Study” by Zemper analyzed 6,229 players from 1986 and 1987. Zemper found that the injury rate was 6.32/per thousand. Sprains of the knee, such as Rodgers mentioned above, and ankles were the most common. Interestingly, there is a 3.1% chance that an ACL tear will occur for a college football athlete. This is not a very significant figure compared to, for example, the most prevalent injury of a muscle or joint sprain, where athletes have a 31.5% chance of having that happen during their career. These are completely different injuries, yet they still often follow a similar recovery process where trainers ease athletes back into activity involving these muscles to build them back up again.</p>

<p>As someone who watches and studies sports I was surprised to not see concussions at the top of the injury list. Concussions bring college football so much attention and media coverage that it is curious that the findings were not more dramatic in this study. One explanation, given this study was done back in 1986 and 1987 is that researchers did not focus their attention on concussions back then the way they do today. Similarly, the Syracuse University athletic trainer and Men's Football strength and conditioning coach discussed muscle sprains as a core focus of their work – much more so than any other aspect.</p>

